		<b>Comment By Bill, 11-08-05</b>
		<p>Maybe it's a typo ... or maybe it's for real: I know the world is desperate for energy wherever it can be found, but in your piece on "Lame Deer, Montana, Northern Cheyenne Reservation," you say the Bureau of Land Management"approved methane exploration on the boarders of the reservation..." How desperate is that?</p>
		
		<b>Comment By Jenny Shank, 11-08-05</b>
		<p>That quote repeats what Gail Small reported in the movie, and I think it's accurate.  There's an update on Montana situation on the website of the organization that produced the documentary, <a href="http://www.newwest.net/?URL=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.katahdin.org%3A">http://www.katahdin.org:</a><br />
<br />
"Since the filming of Homeland ended, the Northern Cheyenne and their allies lost a battle to stop 500 wells per year from being opened up in southeastern Montana. If the mining companiesâ€™ current plans continue, these wells will reach the Cheyenneâ€™s borders within two years."</p>
		
		<b>Comment By Bill, 11-09-05</b>
		<p>I guess I made my point a little too subtly. The sentence in question creates the picture of people -- "boarders" -- on the Northern Cheyenne Reservation who can be explored for methane.</p>
		
		<b>Comment By Jenny Shank, 11-09-05</b>
		<p>Whoops!  Thanks for pointing out the typo.  I'm always happy to supply a mistake that suggests...flatulence as a source of energy resources.  (Has Cheney considered this yet?)  Guess I have to leave it in there now for posterity, though, as these comments won't make sense without it...</p>
		
